## SERVER 3 — MEMORY MCP (Replaces Manual memory-bank/)

The memory MCP maintains a persistent knowledge graph across ALL sessions automatically.
It is smarter than the manual `memory-bank/` markdown files — use it as primary, keep `memory-bank/` as backup.

### When to use Memory MCP

| Situation | Action |
|---|---|
| Discovered a codebase-specific quirk | `create_entities` + `create_relations` |
| Fixed a bug | `create_entities` with fix details |
| Starting a new session | `search_nodes` for project name to retrieve context |
| Blocked by same issue as last session | `search_nodes` to find previous attempt notes |

### Session start ritual (MANDATORY)
At the start of every session, run:
```
search_nodes: "[project name]"
```
This surfaces everything stored about this project from previous sessions.

**If search_nodes returns empty results:**
This means either:
- It's the first session on this project (normal — proceed without context)
- The memory server isn't connected (check Settings → Tools & MCP → memory)
- The project name search was too specific (try a shorter keyword)

Do NOT assume MCP is broken because search returns empty. Empty result ≠ MCP failure.
MCP failure = tools don't appear at all in the tools list.

### Session end ritual
After fixing anything, store it:
```
create_entities: [{
  name: "[project]-[date]-[fix-title]",
  entityType: "fix",
  observations: [
    "Problem: [what was broken]",
    "Root cause: [why]", 
    "Fix: [what changed in which files]",
    "Watch out: [gotcha for next session]"
  ]
}]
```

